The Charter Wars: a generation-long era when major houses armed survey crews and hired mercenary escorts to enforce legal documents at spearpoint.
They arose after the Ninth Meridian catastrophe destroyed centralized ledger authority in the eastern desert road network.
Each faction claimed to be the true inheritor of Measure Law; control belonged to whoever could hold the next cistern gate.
The Reaver Confederates trace their origin to this era: privatized charter militias who outlived their employers and retained procedural habits — seizure inventories, stamped claim-slates, ritualized convoy inspections.
Scorching Sands' kiln-certification systems were maintained through the Charter Wars specifically because they provided fraud-resistant identity verification when all other institutional trust had collapsed.
Warden-Sergeant Caleph Dunmar's forty-three-day defense of the Seven Shade Arches was the defining action of the Charter Wars' late period.
The wars produced the Fracture Era's characteristic mix: local stability at each cistern node; inter-city chaos in the corridors between them.
Water-right arbitration was the primary driver of Charter Wars violence; the caravan economy was secondary.
The era ended not through decisive military victory but through institutional exhaustion: surviving factions negotiated the first inter-city compacts.
Those compacts eventually produced the Five Cities system; the Charter Wars are therefore both the era that destroyed the old order and the condition that made the new order possible.
The Charter Wars' most lasting damage was not physical but archival: records from this period carry contested provenance because every faction produced its own authenticated documents.

