Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant doctrine emerged partly from the Charter Wars: sealed warrants were the era's primary weapon. When documents can be enforced at spearpoint without public documentation or independent review, all governance becomes extortion with paperwork.
Kiess's three-power charter review was designed specifically to prevent Charter Wars conditions from re-emerging.
The founding generation at Kiess knew Charter Wars refugees and heard direct testimony about governance that had no correction mechanism.
Kiess's position: the Charter Wars were not inevitable; they resulted from removing the correction mechanisms that Keeper administration had maintained.
The era is cited in Kiess's charter education as the negative case study: what happens when authority is asserted rather than documented and reviewed.

